I mean  here=E2=80=99s a diagram:
=C2=A0


   =20

And then here=E2=80=99s a slightly annotated diagram
  [1]
:


   =20

In the first diagram, the word =E2=80=9Ccontrols=E2=80=9D appears four time=
s, and if you trace it=C2=A0through,=C2=A0you will see that the board of di=
rectors of OpenAI ultimately=C2=A0controls each entity in the organization.=
 All of=C2=A0OpenAI answers to its ultimate decision-making body, an=C2=A0i=
ndependent nonprofit board of directors who do not own any equity in the Op=
enAI entities and who, broadly speaking, appoint themselves. They answer to=
 their own consciences, not to any investors. =E2=80=9CThe Nonprofit=E2=80=
=99s principal beneficiary is humanity, not OpenAI investors,=E2=80=9D  exp=
lains OpenAI.
In the second diagram, I have written the word =E2=80=9CMONEY=E2=80=9D in l=
arge green letters.
The question is: Is control of OpenAI=C2=A0indicated by the word =E2=80=9Cc=
ontrols,=E2=80=9D or by the word =E2=80=9CMONEY=E2=80=9D?
On Friday, OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonprofit board, its ultimate decision maker,  =
fired Sam Altman, its co-founder and chief executive officer, saying that =
=E2=80=9Che was not consistently candid in his communications with the boar=
d, hindering its ability to exercise its responsibilities.=E2=80=9D Apparen=
tly the board felt that Altman was moving too aggressively to commercialize=
 OpenAI=E2=80=99s products like ChatGPT, and worried that this speed of com=
mercialization raised the risk of creating a rogue artificial intelligence =
that would, you know, murder or enslave humanity.
  [2]
=C2=A0
So it just fired him. =E2=80=9CMicrosoft was shocked Friday when it receive=
d just a few minutes notice=E2=80=9D of the firing, despite having invested=
   some $13 billion in OpenAI. Other investors and employees were similarly=
 blindsided. But that=E2=80=99s the deal! The board decides, and it does no=
t answer to the investors or employees or take their interests into account=
. Its only concern is with =E2=80=9Chumanity.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Except that then OpenAI spent the weekend backtracking and trying to hire A=
ltman back, under pressure from Microsoft Corp., other investors and employ=
ees. Altman=E2=80=99s   conditions for coming back, as far as I can tell, w=
ere that the board had to resign and the governance had to change; I take t=
hat to mean roughly that OpenAI had to become a normal tech company with hi=
m as a typically powerful founder-CEO. They  almost got there, but then did=
 not.   This morning, OpenAI announced that Emmett Shear, the former CEO of=
 Twitch, would be its new interim CEO, while Microsoft announced that it ha=
d hired Altman to lead its in-house artificial intelligence efforts.
Also this morning, =E2=80=9Cmore than 500 of OpenAI's 700-plus employees si=
gned an open letter urging OpenAI's board to resign=E2=80=9D and threatenin=
g to quit to join Altman=E2=80=99s Microsoft team. Incredibly, one of the s=
igners of that letter is Ilya Sutskever, OpenAI=E2=80=99s chief scientist, =
who is on the board and apparently led the effort to fire Altman. =E2=80=9C=
I deeply regret my participation in the board=E2=80=99s actions,=E2=80=9D  =
he tweeted this morning, okay. I wonder if Altman will hire him at Microsof=
t.
So:=C2=A0Is control of OpenAI indicated by the word =E2=80=9Ccontrols,=E2=
=80=9D or by the word =E2=80=9CMONEY=E2=80=9D? In some technical sense, the=
 first diagram is correct; that board really did fire that CEO. In some pra=
ctical sense, if Microsoft has a perpetual license to OpenAI=E2=80=99s tech=
nology=C2=A0and now also most=C2=A0of its employees =E2=80=94=C2=A0 =E2=80=
=9CYou can make the case that Microsoft just acquired OpenAI for $0 and zer=
o risk of an antitrust lawsuit,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 writes Ben Thompson =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the money kind of won.=C2=A0
What should the answer be? Well,=C2=A0it could go either way.=C2=A0You coul=
d=C2=A0write a speculative business fiction story with=C2=A0a plot somethin=
g like this
  [3]
:

The Story of OpenAI
OpenAI was founded as a nonprofit with =E2=80=9Cwith the goal of building s=
afe and beneficial artificial general intelligence for the benefit of human=
ity.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But =E2=80=9Cit became increasingly clear that donations=
 alone would not scale with the cost of computational power and talent requ=
ired to push core research forward,=E2=80=9D so OpenAI created a weird corp=
orate structure, in which a =E2=80=9Ccapped-profit=E2=80=9D subsidiary woul=
d raise billions of dollars from investors (like Microsoft) by offering the=
m a juicy (but capped!) return on their capital, but OpenAI=E2=80=99s=C2=A0=
nonprofit board of directors would ultimately control the organization. =E2=
=80=9CThe for-profit subsidiary is fully controlled by the OpenAI Nonprofit=
,=E2=80=9D whose =E2=80=9Cprincipal beneficiary is humanity, not OpenAI inv=
estors.=E2=80=9D
And this worked incredibly well: OpenAI raised money from investors and use=
d it to build artificial general intelligence (AGI) in a safe and responsib=
le way. The AGI that it built turned out to be astoundingly lucrative and s=
calable, meaning that, like so many other big technology companies before i=
t, OpenAI soon became a gusher of cash with no need to raise any further ou=
tside capital ever again. At which point OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonprofit board l=
ooked around and said =E2=80=9Chey we have been a bit=C2=A0too investor-fri=
endly and not quite humanity-friendly enough; our VCs are rich but billions=
 of people are still poor. So we=E2=80=99re gonna fire our entrepreneurial,=
 commercial, venture-capitalist-type chief executive officer and really get=
 back to=C2=A0our mission of helping humanity.=E2=80=9D And Microsoft and O=
