s is that they work too much, are always at the office, can=E2=80=99t make =
social plans and don=E2=80=99t get much sleep.
If you are a smart ambitious young person you might think to yourself =E2=
=80=9CI would like the upsides of that deal, but without the downsides.=E2=
=80=9D In recent years, we have seen analysts at a number of banks try to r=
enegotiate the deal. At Goldman Sachs Group Inc. a few years ago,   they wr=
ote a whole pitchbook being like =E2=80=9Cwe should be able to go home some=
times.=E2=80=9D
An approach that honestly never occurred to me is: If you get a=C2=A0doctor=
=E2=80=99s note=C2=A0saying that you need eight hours of sleep every night,=
 does the bank have to let you go home at midnight? Like:
=09It does seem like a bad look for the bank not to=C2=A0respect doctor=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0notes?=09What doctor is going to say you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0need eight hours of sleep?

Promising. At the Financial Times,  Sujeet Indap reports that a (former) Ce=
nterview Partners analyst named Kate Shiber tried it, so far=C2=A0without m=
uch success:

She told the firm=E2=80=99s human resources department about her medical co=
ndition and a therapeutic need to get eight to nine hours of sleep a night,=
