<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>The Story of OpenAI</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">OpenAI was founded as a nonprofit with =E2=80=
=9Cwith the goal of building safe and beneficial artificial general intelli=
gence for the benefit of humanity.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But =E2=80=9Cit became inc=
reasingly clear that donations alone would not scale with the cost of compu=
tational power and talent required to push core research forward,=E2=80=9D =
so OpenAI created a weird corporate structure, in which a =E2=80=9Ccapped-p=
rofit=E2=80=9D subsidiary would raise billions of dollars from investors (l=
ike Microsoft) by offering them a juicy (but capped!) return on their capit=
al, but OpenAI=E2=80=99s=C2=A0nonprofit board of directors would ultimately=
 control the organization. =E2=80=9CThe for-profit subsidiary is fully cont=
rolled by the OpenAI Nonprofit,=E2=80=9D whose =E2=80=9Cprincipal beneficia=
ry is humanity, not OpenAI investors.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And this worked incredibly well: OpenAI raised=
 money from investors and used it to build artificial general intelligence =
(AGI) in a safe and responsible way. The AGI that it built turned out to be=
 astoundingly lucrative and scalable, meaning that, like so many other big =
technology companies before it, OpenAI soon became a gusher of cash with no=
 need to raise any further outside capital ever again. At which point OpenA=
I=E2=80=99s nonprofit board looked around and said =E2=80=9Chey we have bee=
n a bit=C2=A0too investor-friendly and not quite humanity-friendly enough; =
our VCs are rich but billions of people are still poor. So we=E2=80=99re go=
nna fire our entrepreneurial, commercial, venture-capitalist-type chief exe=
cutive officer and really get back to=C2=A0our mission of helping humanity.=
=E2=80=9D And Microsoft and OpenAI=E2=80=99s other investors complained, an=
d the board just tapped the diagram =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=C2=A0<em>first=C2=A0=
</em>diagram =E2=80=94=C2=A0and said =E2=80=9Chey, we control this whole th=
ing, that=E2=80=99s the deal you agreed to.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the investors wailed and gnashed their tee=
th but=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s true, that=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>what they agreed =
to, and they had no legal recourse. And OpenAI=E2=80=99s new CEO, and its n=
onprofit board, cut them a check for their capped return and said =E2=80=9C=
bye=E2=80=9D and went back to running OpenAI for the benefit of humanity. I=
t turned out that a benign, carefully governed artificial superintelligence=
 is really good for humanity, and OpenAI quickly solved all of humanity=E2=
=80=99s problems and ushered in an age of peace and abundance in which nobo=
dy wanted for anything or needed any Microsoft products.=C2=A0And capitalis=
m came to an end.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That story is basically coherent, and it is, I=
