<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The math is something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you burn oil or coal to make elect=
ricity, you are taking carbon that was buried in the earth for millions of =
years and putting it into the atmosphere, which is bad. Burning oil or coal=
 for electricity has=C2=A0<em>carbon emissions</em>.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">If you burn=C2=A0<em>trees=C2=A0</em>to make electricity=
, that=E2=80=99s better. You can plant new trees to replace the ones you cu=
t down and burn, and the new trees will take carbon out of the atmosphere a=
nd store it in the trees instead. You can=E2=80=99t do that with coal =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0it will take millions of years to replace any coal you burn =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but you more or less can with trees, over some plausible time h=
orizon.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Burning trees is thus much=
 cleaner than burning coal. Does it have=C2=A0<em>zero emissions?=C2=A0</em=
>I mean? No? But the accounting for this stuff is tricky and stylized. If y=
ou have a program that replaces each tree you cut down with a new tree, ove=
r the long term does that program have zero net emissions? Maybe? Arguably?=
 Depending on how you count?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Carbo=
n capture technology exists to take at least some of=C2=A0the carbon dioxid=
e produced at an electric power plant, capture it, and store it in the eart=
h instead of releasing it into the atmosphere. In theory, you can burn coal=
, capture the carbon, and end up with zero carbon emissions going into the =
atmosphere. (In practice there are issues, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/33431564.256422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDkvdGhlLXN0YXRlLW9mLWNhcmJvbi1jYXB0dXJlLWlzL=
W1vcmUtcHJvbWlzZS10aGFuLXN1Y2Nlc3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEyMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRt=
X21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTIwJnV0bV9=
jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1cb4fb63" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">includ=
ing that</a> =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s so energy-intensive that if you add CCS =
[carbon capture and storage]=C2=A0to a coal plant, you=E2=80=99re roughly d=
oubling the amount of coal you need.=E2=80=9D)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">If you combine Points 3 and 4, you might burn trees to produce=
 electricity (arguably zero emissions) and use carbon capture to store the =
carbon dioxide you produce, resulting in=C2=A0<em>negative emissions</em>. =
Each tree you burn takes carbon out of the atmosphere. As a matter of accou=
nting conventions anyway.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maybe it is even true? I don=E2=80=99t know. <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33431564.256422/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuZXVyYWN0aXYuY29tL3NlY3Rpb24vY2xpbWF0ZS1lbnZpcm9ubWVudC9uZXdzL3=
VrLXN1ZWQtZm9yLWNvdW50aW5nLXdvb2QtYnVybmluZy13aXRoLWNhcmJvbi1jYXB0dXJlLWFzL=
W5lZ2F0aXZlLWVtaXNzaW9ucy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB421d4c24" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Here=
=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Environmental groups are taking the UK governm=
ent to court on Monday (13 November) over plans to spend billions on Biomas=
s with Carbon Capture and Storage (BECCS), a technology aimed at removing C=
O2 from the atmosphere that is also being promoted by the European Union.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plaintiffs say BECCS technology relies on flaw=
ed accounting assumptions because it sees the carbon captured from wood bur=
ning as negative emissions when the process is at best neutral from a clima=
te perspective. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BECCS relies on a simple assumption: Because t=
rees and plants suck up CO2 from the atmosphere when they grow, burning bio=
mass for electricity and capturing the related emissions to store them unde=
rground will result in negative emissions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However, scientists say the negative emissions=
 will only be realised once new trees are planted and grow sufficiently to =
absorb the same amount of carbon dioxide =E2=80=93 a process called the =E2=
=80=98carbon payback period=E2=80=99 that can take several decades. =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Indeed, under UN accounting rules, harvesting =
wood is considered a source of carbon that adds CO2 to the atmosphere and i=
s treated as zero in the energy sector to avoid double-counting the emissio=
ns.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Counting the emissions again when biomass is b=
urned is therefore either a mathematical mistake or a carbon accounting tri=
ck, said Mary Booth, director at PPI, one of the complainants in the UK leg=
al case.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is an accounting gimmick,=E2=80=
=9D Booth told Euractiv, insisting that BECCS provides no net change in car=
bon emissions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CPreviously, the carbon was embodied i=
n the trees and was thus not in the atmosphere. Now, the CO2 is held below =
ground, so is still not in the atmosphere. But there has been no new =E2=80=
=98removal=E2=80=99 of CO2 from the atmosphere,=E2=80=9D Booth stressed.</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Often I find myself <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33431564.256422/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMTcveW91LWNhbi10LXNlbGwtdHJlZXMtbm8=
tb25lLWN1dHMtZG93bj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTIwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYW=
lsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vb=
mV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5d3655d1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">writing around here</=
a> about the accounting gimmick of claiming carbon credits by=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>cutting down trees. The gimmick of claiming the credits by=C2=A0=
<em>cutting them down=C2=A0</em>was new to me.</p>
